        {
            "id": "5f2495b9e9f6964260595a1b",
            "uuid": "c6cb91f2-fa4a-40d4-9b8b-5655a4564a10",
            "title": "5 Quick Steps to Building a Billion Naira Startup in Nigeria. üí∞üí≤",
            "slug": "5-quick-steps-to-entrepreneural-success-in-nigeria",
            "html": "<hr><p>The <s>Easy</s> Hard Way to build a business in Nigeria. How to turn ¬†250,000 USD into 250 billion USD in net-worth like Jeff Bezos.</p><blockquote>It is useless to get up early and to stay up late, eating the food of exhausting labor‚Äî truly he gives sleep to those he loves.</blockquote><p>Anyone who has been running a business in Nigeria for more than 5 years has survived what 90% of most businesses don''t do. Statistics say most businesses fail within the first 3 years, but in Nigeria, many don''t survive the first few months.</p><p>Doing business in Nigeria is like screening a season of the Game of Thrones. Suddenly, your business can be murdered by the Tagaryens‚Ää‚Äî‚ÄäPolice Officers, Lannisters‚Ää‚Äî‚ÄäAgbero Boys, Starks‚Ää‚Äî‚ÄäTax Men, Tyrells‚Ää‚Äî‚ÄäBad Vendors or Baratheons‚Ää‚Äî‚ÄäPotholes, No Electricity, Lack of Infrastructure. And after the death of your business, the plot and twists just keep on in the towns of Westeros, Essos, and Sothoryos‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääyour customers.</p><p>But if you were to ask us‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääwho have survived like Jon Snow‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääabout the quick steps to entrepreneurial success in our nation, follow these steps.</p><ol><li>Hustle Like a Drop Out</li><li>Live Super-Frugally.</li><li>Work like a Donkey</li><li>Stay teachable &amp; humble</li><li>See Failure as an event.</li></ol><p>If when you finish reading this, you still think the steps are quick, then please don''t start a business yet! üòâ</p><p>We would speak to each one now!</p><p><strong>1. Hustle like a dropout, but first, keep your certificate away.</strong></p><p>See, as folks who finished from the most prestigious institution in this country,‚Ää‚Äî‚Ää<em>no bragging rights intended</em>‚Ää‚Äî‚Ää there is little about your ¬†certificate that qualifies for success as an entrepreneur in Nigeria.</p><p>You want to make money, init? Keep your certificate under your bed or just forget it exists entirely.</p><p>1st, 2nd, 3rd Class or No Class, doesn‚Äôt matter. Your lessons are learned as a hustler. Your courses are taken on the road. Your pass or failure is your daily survival.</p><p>Nigeria is a country where Graduates are earning 50k (or less) in air-conditioned offices, whereas school dropouts are cleaning 500k selling in the open spaces of Obalende market.</p><p>Certificates confuse you as to what you should earn‚Ää‚Äî‚Ää<em>assa </em>a 1st Class I should earn min. 500k.</p><p>Hustling establishes what you need to survive‚Äî hustle at all cost, from dawn to dusk.</p><ul><li>Your queen‚Äôs English must be replaced with Pidgin, Yoruba, Igbo &amp; Hausa.</li><li>Your well-ironed shirts must be replaced with wash and dry clothes.</li><li>Your latest iPhone XI must be replaced with <em>palasa </em>Nokia phone with battery that sustains for a week.</li></ul><blockquote>Test: Have you ever hustled your way so much so that people confused you for a low-brow uneducated person? If you do, welcome to the hustle club.</blockquote><p><br></p><p><strong>2. Live Frugally! You don‚Äôt need new dresses in your wardrobe.</strong></p><p>Frugality is the king of survival in Lagos. All those Uber to every meeting; eating in ‚ÄòThe Place‚Äô; having Coldstone ice cream and a movie every weekend is for people earning a lot of their employers money‚Ää‚Äî‚ÄäEmployees.</p><p>As an entrepreneur, you just bike/<em>molue </em>to deliver your orders; eat <em>boli </em>with groundnut as lunch; enjoy your meals without even <em>pomo</em>.</p><p>That‚Äôs the way of the frugal entrepreneur. Not that you won‚Äôt afford and have those things later. But the sacrifice to survive and keep your business afloat makes those as luxuries, now. Just Now!</p><p>YOu must learn to cut costs, eliminate waste and do little with much. You don''t need to always run the generator. You cant afford to be using data to watch irrelevant youtube videos. With your little shop, you can serve customers across Nigeria.</p><p><strong><em>Costs Kill Fast. Sales Cure All. Keep Frugal Always.</em></strong></p><blockquote>Test: have you ever gotten to a point where you bank account looks like JAMB score; like 232?</blockquote><p><strong>3. Work like a Jackal, sleeping 6 hours is sometimes a luxury.</strong></p><p>Lagos is the only country, and we can argue that where there is traffic gridlock from 5 am till 1 am.</p><p>There is nothing about Lagos that is gentle. From the time you come out of your house, if you don‚Äôt have neighbors with ‚Äò<em>i beta pass gen‚Äô</em>, till you return, it is a noisy cantankerous fast-paced movie.</p><p>Say, you have an appointment at 10 am on the Island, you must leave the house at 6 am latest if you stay on the mainland. Sometimes, as early as 4:30 am if you stay at the hinterland‚Ää‚Äî<em>‚ÄäAbule Egba, Mowe, Ajah</em>. Incase you dont know, Lagos traffic is a citizen of Lagos with all rights and priveleges appertaining to a tax player! Don''t mess with Lagos Traffic.</p><p>The hard work in Lagos, just as an employee is insanely intense. People leave their homes at 5am and return at 9pm earliest. A <em>9 am to 5</em> <em>pm </em>job has been turned to a <em>5 am to 9 pm </em>lifestyle.</p><p>But as an entrepreneur, you have to work harder and stay longer. Think about all you need to do as an entrepreneur: call clients, converse for business, handle the traffic, fulfill customer orders, keep tabs on all your social media channels, manage your vendors, and still keep safe against <em>agbero </em>boys.</p><p>Well, if you are doing all these things and more to keep your business afloat, you wouldn‚Äôt be sleeping excessively.</p><blockquote>Test : have you woken up somedays only to be more tired than you slept?</blockquote><p><br></p><p>4. <strong>Stay Teachable, you don‚Äôt learn anything by talking</strong>.</p><p>Everyone has an opinion about everything in Lagos. Ask any average Nigerian what is wrong with the country, and you get a sermon from them. But no one makes money from complaining about itthings. Money is made by observing, learning, asking questions and staying humble all along.</p><p>You just never ever ever know it all in business.</p><p>You would meet all kinds of interesting people in your entrepreneurial journey-land: policemen asking you for your laptop‚Äôs receipt bought 3 years ago; tax officers for taxes in 3 month old business; Molue guys shouting at when they owe you <em>change.</em></p><p>But keep the teachable spirit and stay unprovoked. You would always amazed at the opportunities that lie lurking in daylight‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääeveryone talks about it, no one is doing anything about it.</p><p>The most profitable businesses in Nigeria are from flashes of insight on the daily trends of our challenges‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääask Mr. Dangote who sells sugar &amp; cement, Mr. Adenuga who sells recharge cards or Mr. Pedro who sells oil &amp; gas.</p><blockquote>Test : Have you noticed that it‚Äôs easier to collect 10 naira from 1000 people than to collect 1000 naira from 10 people?</blockquote><p><br></p><p>5. <strong>Failure is an event, not an inheritance from your lineage.</strong></p><p>It is common to hear our superstitious generation say, every failure is a curse from some grandparents and generational umbilical cord. People go on mountains and stay under the sea to remove failure from their life.</p><p>Well, look again, if there is any nation that needs to be cursed, it should be the Germans. The Germans murdered millions of God‚Äôs people, the Jews during WWII, yet today, they are the 4th largest economy in the world with a 4.2 trillion USD. About 10x that of Nigeria.</p><p>Were Germany Nigeria, where would be? You bet, we would still be in the dark ages blaming our ancestors for killing the Jews as the reason for our low standard of living, bad roads and corrupt leaders.</p><p>Enough of that Nonsense! No one is responsible for the outcomes of your life‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääfailure or sucess‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääsave yourself!</p><p>Own your failure, it is an event that happens at a point in time, not an inheritance from any parental ‚Äòbad belle‚Äô. No one is to blame for your failures. But beyond that, don‚Äôt let your failures keep you down! Just dust the back of your sleeves, learn the lessons and forget the details.</p><p>We can guarantee you, in Nigeria, you would fail alotttttt. We mean, a whole lot raised to power 3. But keep pushing forward. Keep keeping on and never say never, irrespective of what you face.</p><p>But failure is a snapshot, so keep the pictures of it out of your live and keep recording the good moments.</p><p><strong>Live Forward. Dont look backward.</strong></p><blockquote>Test: have you ever gotten to a point where you swore to yourself that you would give up. Only to wake up in the morning and promise to fire on?</blockquote><p><br></p><p>Well, those are the 5 <s>quick</s> steps to entrepreneurial success. We would be glad to share in your story?</p><hr><p>Moyotician is the founder and senior tutor of the Lifematics center. She can be reached <a href=\"http://Instagram.com/thelifematics\" rel=\"noopener\">here.</a> <br>Toni is an investor in many startups in Nigeria and loves kids. He can be reached <a href=\"http://twitter.com/iamtoninath\" rel=\"noopener\">here</a></p>",
